{"body":"@thomazrit — generally, I would recommend building anything new as a *table*, not a *view*. View's bring with them a litany of dependency issues that get hard to entangle when you have multiple views derived from the same source.\n\n[Here's an example of the SQL command for building a table](https://github.com/useStable/redshift-sql/blob/0eb43616e3caeb624a6482f4485431efe7ebae08/views/standard_data_refresh/20_prospect_to_org_journey.sql#L49), Claude should be able to one shot this if you prompt it to look at this as an example.","line":null,"path":"views/standard_data_refresh/38_mail_tag_assignments.sql"}
{"body":"The nice part about using tables instead of views is you can also get rid of this `WITH NO SCHEMA BINDING` command, it's unnecessary when building tables instead of views.","line":null,"path":"views/standard_data_refresh/38_mail_tag_assignments.sql"}
{"body":"I'll add, and admittedly it's a bit confusing, even on tables, we still use the leading `view_` nomenclature. This is so we don't have to rebuild a bunch of Metabase dashbaords because across the board, all these tables _used to be_ views.\n\nAll that to say, definitely keep calling this table `view_mail_tag_assignments`, but just note that it's actually table, not a view :)","line":null,"path":"views/standard_data_refresh/38_mail_tag_assignments.sql"}
{"body":"Same as the above file, I'd make this into a table instead of a view.","line":null,"path":"views/standard_data_refresh/39_mail_scan_shares.sql"}
{"body":"Can also get rid of this when making this a table.","line":null,"path":"views/standard_data_refresh/39_mail_scan_shares.sql"}

